          "body": "The psalm's doctrinal foundation arrives at verse 7: 'He is the LORD our God; His judgments are in all the earth.' This is not a general monotheistic statement but a covenant declaration — the God who made a binding oath to Abraham also governs the nations around Abraham's descendants. Verses 8-11 then drill into the covenant's character: it was remembered 'forever' (105:8), commanded 'to a thousand generations' (105:8), made with Abraham (105:9), sworn as an oath to Isaac (105:9), confirmed to Jacob as a statute (105:10), and identified as 'an everlasting covenant' (105:10) with its specific content named in verse 11 — the land of Canaan as Israel's inheritance. The fourfold naming of the patriarchs (Abraham, Isaac, Jacob, Israel) traces the covenant's genealogical transmission and its progressive confirmation. God did not make one promise to one man; He confirmed it at each generational link. The exilic reader — wondering whether the covenant has expired — is told: it is not subject to expiration."
