        "excerpt": "Remember His wonders which He has done, His marvels and the judgments uttered by His mouth, O seed of Abraham, His servant, O sons of Jacob, His chosen ones!",
        "body": "The psalm opens in a mode rare in the Psalter: pure imperative without lament, petition, or confession. Ten commands cascade through six verses, all directed at the covenant community as a worshipping assembly. The structure of the commands is important: the first six (give thanks, call upon, make known, sing, sing praises, speak of His wonders — 105:1-2) are directed outward toward the nations; the next four (glory, seek, seek continually, remember — 105:3-5) are directed inward toward the heart of the seeker. Corporate proclamation and personal interior pursuit are not alternatives; they are the two poles of covenant worship.\n\nThe call to 'make known His deeds among the peoples' (105:1) carries missional force. The nations are not the objects of Israel's contempt but the audience for God's fame. This is precisely the logic of Isaiah 12:4 ('make known His deeds among the peoples') and the Abrahamic promise itself (Genesis 12:3: 'in you all the families of the earth will be blessed'). Israel's rehearsal of what God has done is never merely tribal self-congratulation — it is the disclosure of the character of the universal God to the watching nations.\n\nVerse 5 is the paragraph's interpretive center: 'Remember His wonders which He has done, His marvels and the judgments uttered by His mouth.' The Hebrew *zakhar* ('remember') is the command from which the entire psalm follows. What follows in verses 7-44 is the content of what must be remembered — the wonders, marvels, and judgments are not abstractions but the specific historical events the psalm proceeds to narrate. Howard Hendricks observed that the great enemy of spiritual maturity is not heresy but amnesia — and the psalmist's entire rhetorical strategy is to force the congregation into active, detailed, specific recollection of what God has actually done.\n\nThe address in verse 6 — 'O seed of Abraham, His servant, O sons of Jacob, His chosen ones' — grounds the imperative in covenant identity. The community is not called to remember because they are large or powerful or morally superior. They are called to remember because they are chosen (Hebrew *bachir*) — elect by divine decision alone. The basis of the call to worship is not Israel's achievement but Israel's identity, which is itself entirely a gift.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yadah* (give thanks, 105:1) carries the sense of public acknowledgment with extended hands — it is performative praise, not interior sentiment. *Baqash* (seek, 105:4) denotes urgent, purposeful searching — the same word used of seeking a missing person. *Paneh* (His face, 105:4) — to seek God's face is to pursue personal encounter with the living God, not merely His benefits. *Bachir* (chosen ones, 105:6) — selected by sovereign divine will; the term recurs at 105:43 to bracket the entire narrative."
